title: For Sale:   1920's SMITH & WESSON M&P Hand Ejector
location: NW of City, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
Here is a rare opportunity to acquire what is perhaps the most successful variant of S&W revolver in a very unusual condition: 
 This gun is an earlier (1920s) Military & Police or 'M&P' chambered in the ever popular .38 Special Cartidge and one of the most widely employed revolver types in history. The well worn grips look like later style 'magna's and probably date from the 1940s.
This revolver has seen some very hard use, and looks as if it was constantly carried by it's owner for decades....Like maybe one of the most extreme cases of 'pistol packing' in the 20th Century. 
 At the beginning of the ad I stated that this gun was in unusual condition: Unusually 'broken in' that is.. The finish is finished, the checkered grips  have a checkered past are worn slick, the bore is boring (OK, not rusty),  the single action is still very 'Smithlike'- but the DA has 'hitch in it's get along'. I look at as a built in safety feature to keep youngsters, arthritics, & a certain %-age of women from accidentally firing it on purpose.
Oh it works fine, but the hammer just has a little 'snag' on the way back on double action only.
 This gun has a lot of character & looks as if it were carried by it's owner constantly for many many years. The checkered grips are about slick, and the holster wear long ago went past the blueing & into the steel in a few places...You don't see many like this! 
 But except for that snag in the Double Action mode, the gun is still a very capable shooter. It is, after all, a Smith & Wesson!
 There is a story behind this gun too: It belonged to a recently deceased man that had collected hundreds of high condition rare & expensive firearms. Many were very valuable & rare S&Ws, and lots of those were still as new in their boxes. 
This one must have had a special place in his heart & his collection, is all that I can figure. 
If this gun could talk, it'd probably groan a little bit, forget a detail here & there- but tell a few tales that would span all human emotions. 
Character? Yup.
And plenty of it.

title: For Sale:  1964 Chinese SKS Type 56
postcontent:
This is a 1964 Chinese Norinco Type 56 SKS manufactured at Factory 26 which is where Chinese SKS production first occured. All matching numbers. The receiver has the Factory 26 logo, Chinese characters for Type 56, and the S#. This factory was responsible for producing the military SKS production, not commercial. This SKS was manufactured in 1964 and has the original and correct blade bayonet. The Chinese went to the spike bayonet in 1965. This rifle is in excellent condition and may be unfired. The last 5 digits of the serial number appear on the carrier, bolt, trigger guard, and stock. They were military production, used by the Chinese military. Then basically arsenal refinished (and parts replaced as needed) for the commercial market. The rifle has the original cleaning kit in the butt, original blade bayonet, Chinese sling, and 20 round magazine.

I have many pictures available. Price is $450

title: For Sale:  Preban Polytech M14s/M1A W scope mount + bolt mod
postcontent:
Good afternoon everyone! I've got a DMR's dream here!

Here is an excellent chance to get your hands on a Polytech M14S (M1A), two mags, and a scope mount!

The Polytech M1A has a one-piece FORGED receiver, unlike Springfields, which have a two piece cast receiver. The operating rod is also forged. These rifles are solid! Some were known to have 'soft' bolts, and this one has a hardened US bolt in it. These old baby's are interchangeable with most all M14 parts, and there are still plenty of those out and about. You'll hear a few people complain about these rifles, but the fact is Springfield puts out a few duds too. And these continually go up in price, as more and more people are learning about their potential. And, this is the only way to get a forged 1 piece receiver other than buying a NFA M14.

The rifle is in great shape for being from the late 1980's. As you know, Polytech was banned from importation after 1994, and these occasionally pop up. The walnut is in fantastic shape, the finish is almost 100%, and the rifle has a total round approximation of 100-180 rounds through it.

Oh, and the cleaning kit is original, and has never been opened. Still in the butt stock.

Two mags, a 20 round USGI and a 5 Round.

And a picatinny scope mount kit. Comes with all hardware, box and two ring bases.

This is one of the best setups for a Designated Marksman's Rifle. People who love the M1A builds absolutely drool over these rifles' receivers, and there's no limit to what you could do with it.

Of course, you can shoot to 800 meters all day long (and ACCURATELY!) with the iron sights alone.

Make someone's holidays happy.
$1100.00 

Trades considered, but only goodies of equivocal value. Doesn't have to be guns.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Extra reading, for those who are interested. Taken from Lee Emerson's book on the M14, which can be found here: http://photos.imageevent.com/badgerdog/generalstor age/m14tecnicalfolder/M14%20RHAD%20Text%20Only%20E dition%20090425.pdf

Representatives from Poly Technologies met for five days with Smith Enterprise personnel, with David Keng of Keng’s Firearms acting as translator. The Poly Technologies representatives were supplied with a set of USGI drawings for the M14. During this first meeting, Poly Technologies sent raw forgings and assembled M14 rifles (Polytech serial numbers 00001 through 00005) to Smith Enterprise, Inc. for evaluation and testing. Ron Smith personally test fired these first five Poly Technologies M14 type rifles.

Smith Enterprise thoroughly examined and tested the Poly Technologies receivers and rifles. The receivers were found through spectrum analysis to be made of the Chinese equivalent of AISI 8620 alloy steel, the proper material for M14 receivers.

Karl Maunz was living in Atlanta, GA when Keng’s Firearms imported Poly Technologies M14/S rifles. Keng’s Firearms supplied him with two Poly Technologies M14/S rifles for testing and evaluation. He found the receiver to be made of equivalent AISI 8620 alloy steel. The receiver material testing conducted by Smith Enterprise and Karl Maunz was done independently of each other. The Chinese bolts, however, were not made of the USGI drawing specified steel alloy.
The Smith Enterprise testing included hardness testing of the Poly Technologies receiver core by cutting it apart. One Poly Technologies receiver was tested to destruction by loading ammunition to create excessively high chamber pressure. The very first Poly Technologies receivers were very hard, harder than a file, which left them without the toughness provided by the relatively soft core of receivers made according to USGI specifications. The Chinese quickly corrected this by strictly adhering to the receiver heat treatment procedure.

Think on that. Ron Smith assisted with the construction of the Polytech M14S

title: For Sale/Trade:  german RSI beretta M35 1944
postcontent:
this beretta pistol was included in a delivery of 65,000 Beretta M1934/35 pistols delivered to the German wehrmacht Headquarters in Italy between Aug 1944 and Feb, 1945. Those serial # were 534000/599000.
 After the 8 September 1943 armistice between Italy and the Allies, the Germans saddled Beretta with three engineers from Germany. Moreover the factory was garrisoned by the waffen ss!!! 'armed security service' Weapons of that time, even the ones produced for the Germans, bore the punch mark 4UT, (Quarto Ufficio tecnico di Controllo Armi e Munizioni--4th Technnical Control Unit...
-an C. Still, in Axis Pistols, page 107, states,
"It is likely that almost all of the 4/UT, ...were used by the German Army". He also includes two other variations in this statement, "1944 dated and blank slide Model 1935".
Ugo Menchini, in Pietro Beretta Le Automatiche, regarding an M1934, page 255, states,
"In late 1940 there appears an oval including the punch mark IVU. It refers to the 4th technical Control Unit of the FAG, where inspection was carried out."
 Note that, while they seem to represent the same inspectors, the "IVU" is not the same mark as the "4UT". The IVU would be found on the pre RSI model M1934, and the 4UT would be found on the RSI model M1935.
 These are the reasons why I believe that it is likely that all of the 4UT Berettas WERE RSI pistols!! the IVU and the 4UT were the same office, but under Italian management -the IVU, before the surrender of Italy, and German the 4UT, so after september, 8 1943.........

Mussolini was rescued by German paratroopers led by Otto Skorzeny. He was then installed by the Germans as the President of the Italian Social Republic (RSI). The RSI was to be an Italian regime which was to nominally administer the German-occupied northern Italy. As the Milizia Volontaria per la Sicurezza Nazionale (MVSN, also known as "Black Shirts") was disbanded by the terms of the armistice, the Guardia Nazionale Repubblicana was formed on 24 November 1943. The "Guardia Nazionale Repubblicana" was formed out of local police, ex-army, and others still loyal to the fascist cause.  
 pistol is in near unissued condition and a prime example of strain on axis weapons fabrication late in the war, with tooling and machinery marks throughout, it comes with one extra original period magazine!!!!!!!!
